 capture some of its most memorable moments.Reflecting the great diversity and unpredictability of Arabic literature as the carrier of a major world culture, both pre-modern and modern, the Anthology is divided thematically to highlight modern issues such as love, religion, the human self, human rights, freedom of expression, the environment, violence, secular thought and feminism. The short, easy-to-read texts are accessible to non-specialists, providing an ideal entry point to this extraordinary literature.Key FeaturesA wide thematic and chronological spread including both verse and proseNewly translated texts on a range of subjects such as the occult sciences, heresy, psychological reflections, literary theory, sexual etiquette, man and nature, geographical observations and reflections on world historyIncludes extracts from philosophers, theologians and scientistsMarginal glosses explain key terms, figures and momentsRead the introduction and first few extracts for free (pdf)"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArabic literaturevTranslations into English. 0aArabic literaturexTranslations into English. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aAbi Rabiʿa, ʿUmar ibn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbuʾl Fida,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Abi,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Babi,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Buhturi,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Hutayʾah,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Marzubani,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAl-Sharishi,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb